    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Alcohol Burnoff Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This alcohol burnoff calculator uses the well-established Widmark formula to estimate your blood alcohol concentration (BAC) based on the number of standard drinks consumed, your body weight, biological sex, and the time elapsed since your first drink. Enter the number of standard drinks you have consumed, your weight in kilograms, select your biological sex, and indicate how many hours have passed since you started drinking. Results update instantly as you change any input.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding how your body processes alcohol is important for making informed decisions about your health and safety. Alcohol is metabolized at a relatively fixed rate by the liver, and no amount of coffee, water, or food can speed up this process. This calculator helps you understand the approximate timeline of alcohol elimination from your system, though it is important to remember that individual results will vary.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Widmark Formula Explained</h2>
      <p>
        The Widmark formula, developed by Swedish professor Erik Widmark in the 1930s, remains the standard method for estimating BAC. The formula calculates peak BAC as: <strong>BAC = (alcohol in grams) / (body weight in grams x Widmark factor) x 100</strong>. One standard drink in the United States contains 14 grams of pure alcohol. The Widmark factor (also called the distribution ratio) accounts for the percentage of body weight that is water, where alcohol distributes. For males, this factor is 0.68, and for females, it is 0.55.
      </p>

      <h3>How Alcohol Metabolism Works</h3>
      <p>
        The liver metabolizes alcohol at a nearly constant rate of approximately 0.015 BAC per hour for most people. This means the body eliminates about one standard drink per hour on average. Once your peak BAC is calculated, the current BAC is determined by subtracting the elimination rate multiplied by the hours elapsed. The time until sober is simply the current BAC divided by the elimination rate. Factors such as liver health, genetics, medications, and food intake can affect the actual metabolism rate.
      </p>

      <h3>BAC Levels and Their Effects</h3>
      <p>
        At a BAC below 0.02%, most people experience no noticeable effects and are considered sober. Between 0.02% and 0.06%, mild effects such as slight relaxation and lowered inhibitions begin to appear. Between 0.06% and 0.15%, moderate impairment affects coordination, reaction time, and judgment — this range includes the common legal driving limit of 0.08% in most US states. Above 0.15%, severe impairment occurs, including significant loss of motor control, potential vomiting, and risk of blackout. BAC levels above 0.30% are considered life-threatening.
      </p>

      <h3>Important Safety Information</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator is designed for educational and informational purposes only. BAC estimates are approximate and should never be used as the sole basis for deciding whether it is safe to drive, operate machinery, or engage in any activity requiring full alertness and coordination. Individual metabolism varies widely, and factors such as food consumption, medications, fatigue, and overall health can significantly affect actual impairment. Always consult your healthcare provider if you have questions about alcohol and your health.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How long does it take to burn off one standard drink?</h3>
      <p>
        On average, the body eliminates alcohol at a rate of about 0.015 BAC per hour. For most people, one standard drink (containing 14 grams of pure alcohol) takes approximately 1 to 1.5 hours to metabolize completely. However, this varies based on body weight, gender, liver health, and other individual factors.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the Widmark formula?</h3>
      <p>
        The Widmark formula estimates blood alcohol concentration (BAC) using the equation: BAC = (alcohol in grams / (body weight in grams x Widmark factor)) x 100. The Widmark factor accounts for the difference in body water content between males (0.68) and females (0.55). The formula then subtracts 0.015 per hour to account for metabolism.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a standard drink?</h3>
      <p>
        In the United States, a standard drink contains about 14 grams of pure alcohol. This is equivalent to 12 ounces (355 ml) of regular beer at 5% ABV, 5 ounces (148 ml) of wine at 12% ABV, or 1.5 ounces (44 ml) of distilled spirits at 40% ABV. Different countries may define a standard drink differently.
      </p>

      <h3>Why does gender affect alcohol metabolism?</h3>
      <p>
        Biological sex affects alcohol metabolism primarily because of differences in body water content and body composition. Males typically have a higher percentage of body water (about 68%) compared to females (about 55%), which dilutes alcohol more and results in a lower BAC for the same amount consumed relative to body weight.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I use this calculator to determine if I am safe to drive?</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator provides an estimate only and should never be used as the sole basis for deciding whether to drive. BAC calculations are approximate and do not account for individual variation in alcohol metabolism, food intake, medications, or tolerance. The only safe amount of alcohol before driving is zero. When in doubt, use a designated driver or ride-sharing service.
      </p>

